  "method": "We propose a three-layer calibration stack that converts raw model scores into shift-robust, coverage-controlled probabilities. Layer 1 learns a post-hoc recalibrator that is explicitly regularized to be smooth and trained with a distributionally robust objective, so it does not overfit a single validation set and remains stable under moderate covariate shift. Layer 2 computes instance-wise confidences by decomposing uncertainty into (a) predictive uncertainty from stochastic predictions and (b) fidelity, i.e., how strongly the model prefers the predicted class over plausible alternatives across perturbations; these are combined into per-class probabilities that better track actual correctness. Layer 3 wraps the calibrated probabilities with an online conformal controller that maintains target coverage (e.g., 1−α top-set coverage) under evolving test distributions by adapting a single threshold on-the-fly and performing a final batch recalibration.\n\nShift-robust post-hoc recalibration (Layer 1): Fit a lightweight calibrator g(·) on a held-out set using vector/Dirichlet scaling or a small MLP that maps logits to calibrated class probabilities. Constrain g to be gradient-bounded (e.g., parameterize its last layer with a temperature and sigmoid-limited weights, and add a Jacobian-norm penalty) to keep its sensitivity small. Train g with a robust objective that minimizes worst-case expected calibration loss over a χ²-divergence ball around the (optionally reweighted) calibration distribution. In practice, alternate between (i) adversarial reweighting of calibration samples within the χ² radius and (ii) updating g with clipped/penalized gradients to keep the effective Lipschitz constant low. If unlabeled target data are available, learn density ratios and importance-weight the calibration loss so that the robust objective centers on the target covariates.\n\nUncertainty–fidelity composition (Layer 2): For an input x, generate K stochastic predictions via test-time augmentation, MC dropout, or a small ensemble. Compute normalized predictive entropy Ĥ(x) from the mean softmax. Measure fidelity F_c(x) for each class c as the average top-2 logit margin across the K passes, with a softmax to map margins to [0,1] and temperature tuned on calibration data. Define the per-class calibrated score as s_c(x) = (1 − Ĥ(x)) · F_c(x), then renormalize s over classes to obtain probabilities. When logits are unavailable (e.g., black-box models), approximate F_c via the empirical frequency and consistency of class c across samples, and use normalized sample entropy for (1 − Ĥ). This multiplicative decomposition downweights confident predictions on intrinsically ambiguous inputs and upweights stable, preference-consistent ones.\n\nCoverage control via online conformal calibration (Layer 3): On a split calibration set, compute nonconformity scores A(x, y) = 1 − p_cal(x)[y] using the Layer-1+2 probabilities. Set an initial threshold κ as the (1−α)(n+1)/n quantile (optionally using density-ratio weights to address covariate shift). At test time, output either (a) a probability vector together with a set-valued prediction S(x) = {c : 1 − p_cal(x)[c] ≤ κ} that enjoys 1−α marginal coverage, or (b) a scalar confidence compatible with S by ensuring the true label is in the top-set with probability ≥ 1−α. Update κ online with a decaying step size toward the target coverage based on recent empirical coverage, and periodically perform a batch recalibration on the latest labeled slice. This preserves finite-sample coverage while adapting to drift without retraining the base model.\n\nPractical notes: Train the robust calibrator once per model per domain family; use small K (e.g., 5–10) for Layer 2 to control latency. Evaluate with NLL and ECE (including class- and difficulty-conditional ECE), and verify coverage of S(x) on rolling windows. For safety-critical use, trigger abstention when S(x) is large or when entropy remains high despite recalibration.",
  "rationale": "Overconfidence stems from a mismatch between raw scores and true likelihoods, and it worsens under shift when a recalibrator overfits a single validation distribution. A gradient-bounded recalibrator trained with a χ²-ball robust objective reduces sensitivity to small reweightings of the calibration set, making its mapping stable across nearby test distributions. This directly targets the mechanism by which temperature/Platt scaling can otherwise become brittle out of domain.\n\nInstance-wise uncertainty–fidelity composition improves probability quality by separating aleatoric uncertainty (captured by predictive entropy) from the model’s preference strength for a class (captured by margins/consistency across perturbations). Their product naturally downweights predictions that are either unstable or intrinsically ambiguous, yielding probabilities that better correlate with correctness.\n\nFinally, conformal coverage provides finite-sample guarantees on set-valued predictions independent of score calibration details, and an online threshold update tracks nonstationarity. Together, these layers yield calibrated probabilities that remain meaningful under distribution shift and offer a controllable safety net when the shift is too large for precise scalar calibration.",
