  "method": "We propose SCOPE-Cal: a shift-aware calibration pipeline that combines a deterministic uncertainty head, an online adaptive calibrator, and a lightweight conformal layer for risk control. At inference time, the base model produces logits for class probabilities and a companion uncertainty score. The scores are first mapped through a post-hoc calibrator trained offline, then dynamically adjusted online to track distribution shifts. For high-stakes use, we optionally return conformal prediction sets that preserve target coverage even as the data drifts.\n\nOffline, train the task model as usual, then freeze it and attach a prototype-based uncertainty head at the pre-logit latent layer. This head learns a small set of prototypes and outputs a single-pass confidence score in [0,1] indicating how typical the example is with respect to learned class-conditional structure. In parallel, fit a standard multiclass post-hoc calibrator on in-distribution validation data (e.g., vector temperature scaling or a low-rank matrix/bias map) by minimizing NLL; this yields a static mapping g0(z) from logits to calibrated probabilities that is optimal for the source domain.\n\nOnline, maintain a tiny stateful calibrator g_t parameterized by a few variables (e.g., global temperature T, optional per-class biases) initialized from g0. Update g_t whenever small batches of labels arrive using a Kalman-filter-like step: treat batch-wise miscalibration statistics (e.g., NLL residuals, reliability within probability bins) as noisy observations of the optimal parameter change and adjust T and biases accordingly. Estimate the observation and process noise with exponential moving averages so the update rate adapts to label scarcity and stochasticity. Weight each example’s contribution by its uncertainty score, giving larger updates for higher-uncertainty samples that are more indicative of shift. When labels are temporarily unavailable, apply a safe, ranking-preserving softening p' = normalize(p^(1 + λ·u)) that reduces confidence proportional to uncertainty u, with λ tuned on source data and adjusted upward if shift detectors flag drift.\n\nFor coverage guarantees under shift, run a lightweight, rolling weighted conformal layer on top of g_t. Maintain a small buffer of the most recent labeled examples and compute nonconformity scores (e.g., −log calibrated probability of the true class). Partition the buffer into uncertainty bins and compute per-bin quantile thresholds with optional importance weights from a domain classifier (to partially correct covariate shift). At prediction time, in addition to calibrated probabilities, return a prediction set containing all labels whose nonconformity is below the per-bin threshold for the test point’s uncertainty bin; this preserves approximate coverage overall and within uncertainty strata while keeping sets small on in-distribution inputs.",
  "rationale": "Modern deep models are overconfident because fixed post-hoc calibrators are optimized for the training distribution and do not adapt when the data drifts. SCOPE-Cal addresses this by (1) learning a deterministic uncertainty score that detects atypical inputs with a single forward pass; (2) using that score to focus online calibration updates on the most shift-informative examples and to safely soften probabilities when labels are sparse; and (3) adaptively tracking the best calibration parameters with a Kalman-style update that is robust to noisy, intermittent supervision. This combination preserves excellent in-distribution calibration while remaining responsive under distribution shift.\n\nFinally, the optional conformal layer adds distribution-agnostic risk control: even if probabilities degrade temporarily during a sharp shift, prediction sets maintain target coverage, and conditioning on uncertainty bins helps keep sets tight where the model is confident and expand them only where warranted. The result is reliable probabilities for downstream decision-making, with an explicit mechanism to handle and report uncertainty under shift.",
